Goldenfeld2007 requested new ways of approaches to studying bacterial evolutions.



The question has been tried using 
mostly limited sets of genes provided by a database called Multi Locus Sequence
Typing (MLST) (Maiden1998).  It has not yet been addressed in genomic scale.  

Population genetic studies of SDE.
McMillan2010

Find molecular markers to discrminate SDE and SPY.
McMillan2010b

An example where virulence genes were transferred.
Rosas-Magallanes2006

Bacteria evolve vertically and horizontally. 
Clonal evolution of bacteria allows us to trace their history via species
trees. 
Homologous recombination among 
closely related species and gene transfer between distantly related
species shape the diversity of bacterial speices.  The diversification of
bacterial species via horizontal gene flow make inferring species trees
a formidable statistical problem.  Researchers tend to abandon evolutionary
models of bifurcating tree, and embrace web-like network models. Web-like
network models are difficult to interpret.
Species boundaries among bacterial
species formed horizontally are blurred.
Bacterial conjugation, transformation, and transduction induce homologous
recombinations that are biological mechanisms through which 
a donor bacterium gives a recipient bacterium genetic segments. 
Inferring recombination events between bacterial species would facilitate
understanding of gene flow from a bacterial species to another.
 
High-throughput genotyping efforts of many bacterial species are underway.
Methodological developments keep pace with the endeavor. Notably, 


